                  , from his person
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18210718-36-person353">
                  WILLIAM 
                  THOMPSON
               <interp inst="t18210718-36-person353" type="surname" value="THOMPSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18210718-36-person353" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18210718-36-person353" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a <rs id="t18210718-36-viclabel205" type="occupation">ship-owner</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18210718-36-victim352 t18210718-36-viclabel205"></join>. I was in the <placeName id="t18210718-36-crimeloc206">Strand</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18210718-36-crimeloc206" type="placeName" value="Strand"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18210718-36-crimeloc206" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18210718-36-off203 t18210718-36-crimeloc206"></join>, on the 27th of June, in the evening - my son was a little behind me. I heard him call out, turned round, and saw the prisoner run off with a handkerchief in his hand, and my son after him, calling Stop thief! I felt, and missed mine. He was secured. A gentleman brought me my handkerchief after we returned from the police vessel.</p>
               <p>WILLIAM THOMPSON, JUN. I was walking about ten yards behind my father, and saw the prisoner take my father's handkerchief out of his pocket - I immediately called out Stop thief! and he ran off; I pursued, and never lost sight of him until he was caught; he was putting it in his pocket.</p>
               <p>ROBERT M'CLEARA. I am a Thames Police officer. I heard the cry, saw the prisoner running, and stopped him in the Strand - I took him down Arundel-street. He said,</p>
               <p>"Don't say I took the handkerchief." About a dozen came round and rescued him - I pursued, and took him again without losing sight of him. He said again,</p>
               <p>"Why did you say I took the handkerchief; don't you say I took it." His left-hand pocket was turned inside out.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18210718-36-person354">
                  WILLIAM 
                  NESBITT
               <interp inst="t18210718-36-person354" type="surname" value="NESBITT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18210718-36-person354" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18210718-36-person354" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the street-keeper. I assisted in securing him after he escaped. I did not see him in possession of the handkerchief.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I was coming down the Strand - I heard the cry, and a man stopped me.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18210718-36-verdict207" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18210718-36-verdict207" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 17.</p>
